               <msContents>
                  <msItem n="1" xml:id="MS_Selden_Supra_93-item1">
                     <author key="person_59077661">Thomas à Kempis</author>
                     <title key="work_4859">Imitatio Christi</title>
                     <finalRubric>Explicit Musica ecclesiastica, tres continens partes</finalRubric>
                     <note>With lists of chapters of parts 2 and 3, but without the fourth book, and wanting a leaf or two at beginning.</note>
                     <colophon>Scriptus erat liber iste anno Verbi incarnati Ihesu millesimo quadringensimo . lxix°. Et anno ... domini Edwardi ... regis Anglie ... octauo . Eleyson ymas</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                  </msItem><msItem xml:id="MS_Selden_Supra_93-item1a">
                     <locus>(fol. 135)</locus>
                     <note>Some prayers and theological notes follow, and near the end a praise of London, 'Turris, campana, pons, flumen, femina, lana, | et decus ecclesie sunt tibi, Londonie . Hec dicta sunt [per] Sigismundum imperatorem <supplied>de</supplied> Londoniis tem<supplied>pore</supplied> Henrici regis quinti', i.e. circa A.D. 1416 (fol. 142). The name of R<supplied>obert</supplied> Bale occurs at fol. 138v.</note> <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
             
